uild/reports to be sure. Maybe the dynamic-access-coverage was generated before the new test, but I see there's no line. Should I check the timestamp? Hmm, maybe there’s a \\\"COVERAGE.md\\\" file that explains the algorithm.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_hqMMAtvBtC18nWMRB60FNBWw|fc_08e539bff7d68b39016a11604e3edc81958860983d3e4825dd", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "COVERAGE.md", "limit": 200}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 524, "output": 1008, "cacheRead": 90112, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 91644, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779523644229, "responseId": "resp_08e539bff7d68b39016a11603d3250819592de02376fc1a458"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_hqMMAtvBtC18nWMRB60FNBWw|fc_08e539bff7d68b39016a11604e3edc81958860983d3e4825dd", "toolName": "read", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "# Coverage\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-22\n\n![Coverage over Time](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/oracle/graalvm-reachability-metadata/stats/coverage/latest/metrics-over-time.svg#gh-light-mode-only)\n![Coverage over Time](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/oracle/graalvm-reachability-metadata/stats/coverage/latest/metrics-over-time-dark.svg#gh-dark-mode-only)\n\n## Libraries\n\n| Library | Versions | Description | Dynamic access coverage |\n| --- | --- | --- | ---: |\n| `antlr:antlr` | [2.7.6](metadata/antlr/antlr/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> ANTLR 2 is a parser generator and runtime for building lexers, parsers, tree parsers, compilers, and translators from grammar files. The antlr artifact provides the Java tool and runtime classes used to generate and run parsers, with code generation support for Java, C++, C#, and Python.</details> | [80.0% (12/15 calls)](stats/antlr/antlr/) |\n| `aopalliance:aopalliance` | [1.0](metadata/aopalliance/aopalliance/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> AOP Alliance defines a small set of standard Java interfaces for aspect-oriented programming, especially method and constructor interception. Libraries use these interfaces to expose portable advice and interceptor contracts without depending on a particular AOP implementation.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/aopalliance/aopalliance/) |\n| `app.cash.sqldelight:async-extensions-jvm` | [2.3.2](metadata/app.cash.sqldelight/async-extensions-jvm/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> SQLDelight Async Driver Extensions provides Kotlin coroutine helpers for SQLDelight asynchronous drivers on the JVM. It adds suspend functions that await driver operations and query results, including list, single-row, and nullable single-row result helpers.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/app.cash.sqldelight/async-extensions-jvm/) |\n| `app.cash.sqldelight:coroutines-extensions-jvm` | [2.3.2](metadata/app.cash.sqldelight/coroutines-extensions-jvm/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> SQLDelight Coroutines Extensions provides Kotlin extension functions that expose SQLDelight Query objects as kotlinx.coroutines Flow streams. It also supplies Flow mapping helpers that asynchronously collect one row, optional or default rows, non-null rows, or lists from emitted queries.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/app.cash.sqldelight/coroutines-extensions-jvm/) |\n| `app.cash.sqldelight:jdbc-driver` | [2.3.2](metadata/app.cash.sqldelight/jdbc-driver/index.json) | <details><summary>Show</summary> SQLDelight JDBC Driver provides a JVM SqlDriver implementation backed by JDBC connections for SQLDelight-generated Kotlin database code. It maps JDBC ResultSet and PreparedStatement operations into SQLDelight cursor, statement, transaction, and connection APIs so applications can use JDBC-accessible databases.</details> | [100.0% (0/0 calls)](stats/app.cash.sqldelight/jdbc-driver/) |\n| `app.cash.sqldelight:runtime-jvm` | [2.3.2](metadata/app.cash.sqldelight/runtime